29:11.079 --> 29:18.332
example, I got $250,000, which I should have been 
satisfied to build a 65-foot vessel with. I've

29:18.352 --> 29:21.258
managed to get another $50,000 of return 
overhead. That gave me $300,000. And then I shot

29:23.738 --> 29:25.060
for an 80-foot. Well, the size goes up to the cube of 
the length. And instead of getting a vessel that

29:27.644 --> 29:32.571
would be extremely limited, I built the Ocona, 
which is operating out of Alaska now. And it's

29:33.252 --> 29:36.457
doing a fine job.

29:37.539 --> 29:44.589
The first thing I look for, first of all, you have to 
have a vessel that will do the work you want. But

29:44.609 --> 29:47.113
then I'd look for creature comfort. Make the 
quarters as good as I can, the eating facilities as

29:47.133 --> 29:51.940
good as I can.

